Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop onto a large
#baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, sprinkle
over the @dried rosemary{1}(sprig), then toss to coat. Spread out in a single
layer. TIP: Use two #baking trays{} if necessary. When the oven is hot, roast on
the middle shelf until golden, ~{30-40%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pop a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, lay the @duck breasts{2} in the pan, skin-side down, and fry until
the skin is golden, ~{6-8%minutes}. Flip, then sear the other side for
~{1%minute} more.

Transfer to a baking tray, skin-side up, and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.
Roast on the top shelf of your oven until cooked, ~{16-18%minutes}.

Once cooked, transfer to a #plate{}. Cover and rest for ~{10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw duck and its
> packaging. The duck is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the duck roasts, trim the bottom 2cm from the @asparagus{100} and discard.
Trim and halve the @Chantenay carrots{150} lengthways (no need to peel). Halve,
peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1} into small pieces.

Once the potatoes have been in the oven for ~{10%minutes}, turn them and push
them to one half of the baking tray. Add the carrots to the other half, then
drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast on the middle shelf for the remaining time until the potatoes are golden
and the carrots are tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

When the duck has roasted and is resting, wipe out the (now empty)
frying pan and pop on medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, add the shallot and fry until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in the @fig jam{40}, @chicken stock paste{10} and @water for the sauce{150},
then bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{6-7%minutes}. Add a splash
of water if it's a little thick. Remove from the heat.

Meanwhile, bring a large #saucepan{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp} to the boil
for the asparagus.

When the water is boiling, add the asparagus and cook until tender,
~{1-2%minutes}.

Drain well in a #colander{}, then pop back into the saucepan. Drizzle with
@oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then toss to coat.

Once the duck has rested, cut widthways into 1cm slices and fan out on your
plates.

Spoon over the fig sauce and serve with the roasted potatoes, carrots and
asparagus alongside. Enjoy!